definition.value: A segmented viral genome consisting of more than three sub-genomic nucleic acids but each nucleic acid is packaged into a different virion.
A viral genome composed of deoxyribonucleic acid.
A viral genome composed of ribonucleic acid. This results in genome replication and expression of genetic information being inextricably linked.
A viral genome composed of double stranded RNA.
A viral genome composed of single stranded RNA of either positive or negative sense.
A single stranded RNA genome with the same nucleotide polarity as mRNA.
A single stranded RNA genome with the opposite nucleotide polarity as mRNA.
A RNA genome that contains coding regions that are either positive sense or negative sense on the same RNA molecule.
The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles. It comprises numerous regularly arranged subunits, or capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles -  the subunits are arranged to form a protein helix with the genetic material contained within. Tobacco mosaic virus has such a capsid structure.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles -  the subunits are arranged to form an icosahedron, a solid with 20 faces and 12 vertices. Icosahedral capsids have 12 pentamers plus 10(T-1) hexamers, where T is the triangulation number. Tobacco satellite necrosis virus has such a capsid structure.
The lipid bilayer of a virion that surrounds the protein capsid. May also contain glycoproteins.
A structure lying between the capsid and envelope of a virus, varying in thickness and often distributed asymmetrically.
Specific locations and structures in the virus infected cell involved in replicating the viral genome.
A nucleoprotein complex containing viral genetic material and associated viral and host proteins, which is capable of inserting a viral genome into a host genome.
Specific locations and structures in the virus infected cell involved in transcribing the viral genome.
Specific locations and structures in the virus infected cell involved in assembling new virions.
The name given to a viral genome after it has been integrated into the host genome -  particularly applies to retroviruses and is a required part of the retroviral replication cycle.

label.value: modulation by virus of host transcription

definition.value: Any process in which a virus modulates the frequency, rate or extent of its host's transcription.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with pyrimidine nucleotide, any compound consisting of a pyrimidine nucleoside esterified with (ortho)phosphate.

Catalysis of the removal of damaged bases by cleaving the N-C1' glycosidic bond between the target damaged DNA base and the deoxyribose sugar. The reaction releases a free base and leaves an apurinic|apyrimidinic (AP) site.
Catalysis of the transfer of a palmitoyl group to a nitrogen atom on the acceptor molecule.
Catalysis of the transfer of a myristoyl (CH3-[CH2]12-CO-) group to an acceptor molecule.
Catalysis of the reaction -  an aromatic aldehyde + NAD+ + H2O -eq- an aromatic acid + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  phenanthrol + X-SO3(-) -eq- HX + phenanthrylsulfate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  phenanthrol + glucose -eq- phenanthryl-beta-D-glucopyranoside + H2O.
Catalysis of a monooxygenase reaction in which oxygen is incorporated into limonene.
Catalysis of the reaction -  catechol + O2 -eq- a muconate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  benzaldehyde + NAD(P)+ + H2O -eq- benzoate + NAD(P)H + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  6-hydroxynicotine + H2O + O2 -eq- 1-(6-hydroxypyrid-3-yl)-4-(methylamino)butan-1-one + hydrogen peroxide.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a dihydroxyfluorene + O2 -eq- the corresponding 2-hydroxy-4-(oxo-1,3-dihydro-2H-inden-ylidene) but-2-enoic acid.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a phenanthrene dioxide + H2O -eq- a dihydrodiolphenanthrene.
Catalysis of the reaction -  phenanthrene-9,10-oxide + H2O -eq- trans-9,10-dihydrodiolphenanthrene.

label.value: hydrolase activity, acting on acid halide bonds, in C-halide compounds

definition.value: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of any acid halide bond in substances containing halogen atoms in organic linkage.
Catalysis of the reaction -  choline + 2 reduced ferredoxin + O2 + 2 H+ -eq- betaine aldehyde hydrate + 2 oxidized ferredoxin + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction -  alpha-D-glucosamine 1-phosphate + acetyl-CoA -eq- N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosamine 1-phosphate + CoA + H(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  protein N6-(4-aminobutyl)-L-lysine + donor-H2 + O2 -eq- protein N6-((R)-4-amino-2-hydroxybutyl)-L-lysine + acceptor + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + 2'-deoxynucleoside -eq- ADP + 2'-deoxynucleoside 5'-phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a thioglucoside + H2O -eq- a thiol + a sugar.
Catalysis of the reaction -  N6-dimethylallyladenine + acceptor + H2O -eq- adenine + 3-methylbut-2-enal + reduced electron acceptor.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + myo-inositol -eq- ADP + 1D-myo-inositol 3-phosphate.

Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-pantolactone + NADP+ -eq- 2-dehydropantolactone + NADPH + H+. The reaction is B-specific (i.e. the pro-S hydrogen is transferred from the 4-position of reduced nicotinamide cofactor) with respect to NADP+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  glyoxylate + H(2)O + propanoyl-CoA -eq- 2-hydroxyglutarate + CoA + H(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  8-phospho-3-deoxy-D-manno-oct-2-ulosonate + H(2)O -eq- 3-deoxy-D-manno-octulosonate + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ADP-sugar + H2O -eq- AMP + sugar 1-phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  4-aminobutanal + NAD+ + H2O -eq- 4-aminobutanoate + NADH + 2 H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  D-arabinose 5-phosphate -eq- D-ribulose 5-phosphate + 2 H(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-1-aminopropan-2-ol + NAD(+) -eq- aminoacetone + H(+) + NADH.
Catalysis of the reaction -  D-cysteine + H2O -eq- sulfide + NH3 + pyruvate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  3-chloro-D-alanine + H2O -eq- pyruvate + chloride + NH3.
